The close relationship between tree ring cellulose δ<sup>18</sup>O and the Indian summer monsoon (ISM) can be explained by oxygen isotope fractionation mechanisms. Our results indicate that the regional tree ring cellulose δ<sup>18</sup>O record is suitable for reconstructing high-resolution changes in the ISM. The record exhibits significant inter-annual and centennial variations. Inter-annual changes are closely related to the El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO), which indicates that the ISM was affected by ENSO in the past. However, the ISM-ENSO relationship was not consistent over time. Centennial changes in the regional tree ring δ<sup>18</sup>O record indicate a trend of weakened ISM intensity since 1820. Decreasing ISM activity is also observed in various high-resolution ISM records from southwest China and Southeast Asia, and may be the result of reduced land-ocean thermal contrasts since 1820 CE.
